===subject:Reply to Kristin
===from:Stephenie Buice
===date:Tue Dec 10 22:28:19 2002
===message:I definitely agree that materialism came to a forefront in the 1950's.  I believe that all of the propaganda helped instill the desires of the American people.  There were several countries that did not have much, and people of the United States were depicted as having much.  This probably helped engage the "credit" spending.  Even though Americans could not afford things, they thought it was necessary (it was shown that Americans were prosperous) to stand up to what was being said. One segment of Episode 13 sticks out in my mind.  It was the lady talking about a car being a status symbol.  If you were any one, you would own a car (whether you could afford one or not) just to be "accepted" and fit in.  This holds true to this day.  Most women would be more easily persuaded to date a jerk in a Lexus rather than a sweetheart in a Pinto. How sad is that?
